281  /// rather than three template functions, because Cython does

284  class MemoryKnight
285  {
286  public:

288  ~MemoryKnight(){}; ///< Default Destructor

291  /// its default constructor.

294 
295  /// Creates a new instance of type T, using T's default
296  /// constructor, at a given location.
297  /// \param void * ptr, location to create T instance
298  /// \return value of ptr recast as T *
299  T * renew(void * ptr){return new (ptr) T();};

471  /// Retrieves the \a nth index out of the dataset \a dset (which has an HDF5
472  /// datatype \a dtype). The value is returned as the C/C++ type given by \a T.
473  template <typename T>
474  T get_array_index(hid_t dset, int n, hid_t dtype=H5T_NATIVE_DOUBLE)
475  {
476  hsize_t count [1] = {1};
477  hsize_t offset [1] = {static_cast<hsize_t>(n)};
478 
479  hid_t dspace = H5Dget_space(dset);
480  hsize_t npoints = H5Sget_simple_extent_npoints(dspace);
481 
482  //Handle negative indices
483  if (n < 0)
484  offset[0] = offset[0] + npoints;
485 
486  //If still out of range we have a problem
487  if (npoints <= offset[0])
488  throw HDF5BoundsError();
489 
490  H5Sselect_hyperslab(dspace, H5S_SELECT_SET, offset, NULL, count, NULL);
491 
492  //Set memmory hyperspace
493  hsize_t dimsm[1] = {1};
494  hid_t memspace = H5Screate_simple(1, dimsm, NULL);
495 
496  hsize_t count_out [1] = {1};
497  hsize_t offset_out [1] = {0};
498 
499  H5Sselect_hyperslab(memspace, H5S_SELECT_SET, offset_out, NULL,
500  count_out, NULL);
501 
502  T data_out [1];
503  H5Dread(dset, dtype, memspace, dspace, H5P_DEFAULT, data_out);
504 
505  return data_out[0];
506  };

511  /// Reads in data from an HDF5 file as a C++ set. \a T should roughly match
512  /// \a dtype.
513  /// \param h5file HDF5 file id for an open file.
514  /// \param data_path path to the data in the open file.
515  /// \param dtype HDF5 data type for the data set at \a data_path.
516  /// \return an in memory set of type \a T.
517  template <typename T>
518  std::set<T> h5_array_to_cpp_set(hid_t h5file, std::string data_path, hid_t dtype=H5T_NATIVE_DOUBLE)
519  {
520  std::set<T> cpp_set = std::set<T>();
521  hsize_t arr_len[1];
522  hid_t dset = H5Dopen2(h5file, data_path.c_str(), H5P_DEFAULT);
523 
524  // Initilize to dataspace, to find the indices we are looping over
525  hid_t arr_space = H5Dget_space(dset);
526  int arr_dim = H5Sget_simple_extent_dims(arr_space, arr_len, NULL);
527 
528  // Read in data from file to memory
529  T * mem_arr = new T [arr_len[0]];
530  H5Dread(dset, dtype, H5S_ALL, H5S_ALL, H5P_DEFAULT, mem_arr);
531 
532  // Load new values into the set
533  cpp_set.insert(&mem_arr[0], &mem_arr[arr_len[0]]);
534 
535  H5Dclose(dset);
536 
537  delete[] mem_arr;
538  return cpp_set;
539  };

542  /// Reads in data from an HDF5 file as a 1 dimiensional vector. \a T should roughly
543  /// match \a dtype.
544  /// \param h5file HDF5 file id for an open file.
545  /// \param data_path path to the data in the open file.
546  /// \param dtype HDF5 data type for the data set at \a data_path.
547  /// \return an in memory 1D vector of type \a T.
548  template <typename T>
549  std::vector<T> h5_array_to_cpp_vector_1d(hid_t h5file, std::string data_path,
550  hid_t dtype=H5T_NATIVE_DOUBLE)
551  {
552  std::vector<T> cpp_vec;
553  hsize_t arr_dims [1];
554  hid_t dset = H5Dopen2(h5file, data_path.c_str(), H5P_DEFAULT);
555 
556  // Initilize to dataspace, to find the indices we are looping over
557  hid_t arr_space = H5Dget_space(dset);
558  int arr_ndim = H5Sget_simple_extent_dims(arr_space, arr_dims, NULL);
559 
560  // Read in data from file to memory
561  T mem_arr [arr_dims[0]];
562  H5Dread(dset, dtype, H5S_ALL, H5S_ALL, H5P_DEFAULT, mem_arr);
563 
564  // Load new values into the vector
565  cpp_vec.assign(mem_arr, mem_arr+arr_dims[0]);
566 
567  H5Dclose(dset);
568  return cpp_vec;
569  };

572  /// Reads in data from an HDF5 file as a 2 dimiensional vector. \a T should roughly
573  /// match \a dtype.
574  /// \param h5file HDF5 file id for an open file.
575  /// \param data_path path to the data in the open file.
576  /// \param dtype HDF5 data type for the data set at \a data_path.
577  /// \return an in memory 2D vector of type \a T.
578  template <typename T>
579  std::vector< std::vector<T> > h5_array_to_cpp_vector_2d(hid_t h5file, std::string data_path,
580  hid_t dtype=H5T_NATIVE_DOUBLE)
581  {
582  hsize_t arr_dims [2];
583  hid_t dset = H5Dopen2(h5file, data_path.c_str(), H5P_DEFAULT);
584 
585  // Initilize to dataspace, to find the indices we are looping over
586  hid_t arr_space = H5Dget_space(dset);
587  int arr_ndim = H5Sget_simple_extent_dims(arr_space, arr_dims, NULL);
588 
589  // Read in data from file to memory
590  // Have to read in as 1D array to get HDF5 and new keyword
591  // to play nice with each other
592  T mem_arr [arr_dims[0] * arr_dims[1]];
593  H5Dread(dset, dtype, H5S_ALL, H5S_ALL, H5P_DEFAULT, mem_arr);
594 
595  // Load new values into the vector of vectors, using some indexing tricks
596  std::vector< std::vector<T> > cpp_vec (arr_dims[0], std::vector<T>(arr_dims[1]));
597  for(int i = 0; i < arr_dims[0]; i++)
598  {
599  cpp_vec[i].assign(mem_arr+(i*arr_dims[1]), mem_arr+((i+1)*arr_dims[1]));
600  };
601 
602  H5Dclose(dset);
603  return cpp_vec;
604  };

607  /// Reads in data from an HDF5 file as a 3 dimiensional vector. \a T should roughly
608  /// match \a dtype.
609  /// \param h5file HDF5 file id for an open file.
610  /// \param data_path path to the data in the open file.
611  /// \param dtype HDF5 data type for the data set at \a data_path.
612  /// \return an in memory 3D vector of type \a T.
613  template <typename T>
614  std::vector< std::vector< std::vector<T> > > h5_array_to_cpp_vector_3d(hid_t h5file,
615  std::string data_path,
616  hid_t dtype=H5T_NATIVE_DOUBLE)
617  {
618  hsize_t arr_dims [3];
619  hid_t dset = H5Dopen2(h5file, data_path.c_str(), H5P_DEFAULT);
620 
621  // Initilize to dataspace, to find the indices we are looping over
622  hid_t arr_space = H5Dget_space(dset);
623  int arr_ndim = H5Sget_simple_extent_dims(arr_space, arr_dims, NULL);
624 
625  // Read in data from file to memory
626  // Have to read in as 1D array to get HDF5 and new keyword
627  // to play nice with each other
628  T mem_arr [arr_dims[0] * arr_dims[1] * arr_dims[2]];
629  H5Dread(dset, dtype, H5S_ALL, H5S_ALL, H5P_DEFAULT, mem_arr);
630 
631  // Load new values into the vector of vectors of vectors, using some indexing tricks
632  std::vector< std::vector< std::vector<T> > > cpp_vec (arr_dims[0], std::vector< std::vector<T> >(arr_dims[1], std::vector<T>(arr_dims[2])));
633  for(int i = 0; i < arr_dims[0]; i++)
634  {
635  for(int j = 0; j < arr_dims[1]; j++)
636  {
637  cpp_vec[i][j].assign(mem_arr+((i*arr_dims[1]*arr_dims[2]) + (j*arr_dims[2])), mem_arr+((i*arr_dims[1]*arr_dims[2]) + ((j+1)*arr_dims[2])));
638  };
639  };
640 
641  H5Dclose(dset);
642  return cpp_vec;
643  };

661  /// Constructor to load in data upon initialization. \a T should roughly
662  /// match \a dtype.
663  /// \param h5file HDF5 file id for an open file.
664  /// \param data_path path to the data in the open file.
665  /// \param dtype HDF5 data type for the data set at \a data_path.
666  HomogenousTypeTable(hid_t h5file, std::string data_path, hid_t dtype=H5T_NATIVE_DOUBLE)
667  {
668  hid_t h5_set = H5Dopen2(h5file, data_path.c_str(), H5P_DEFAULT);
669  hid_t h5_space = H5Dget_space(h5_set);
670  hid_t h5_type = H5Dget_type(h5_set);
671 
672  // set path
673  path = data_path;
674 
675  // set shape
676  shape[0] = H5Sget_simple_extent_npoints(h5_space);
677  shape[1] = H5Tget_nmembers(h5_type);
678 
679  // set cols
680  std::string * cols_buf = new std::string [shape[1]];
681  for(int n = 0; n < shape[1]; n++)
682  cols_buf[n] = H5Tget_member_name(h5_type, n);
683  cols.assign(cols_buf, cols_buf+shape[1]);
684 
685  // set data
686  hid_t col_type;
687  T * col_buf = new T [shape[0]];
688 
689  data.clear();
690  for(int n = 0; n < shape[1]; n++)
691  {
692  // Make a compound data type of just this column
693  col_type = H5Tcreate(H5T_COMPOUND, sizeof(T));
694  H5Tinsert(col_type, cols[n].c_str(), 0, dtype);
695 
696  // Read in this column
697  H5Dread(h5_set, col_type, H5S_ALL, H5S_ALL, H5P_DEFAULT, col_buf);
698 
699  // save this column as a vector in out data map
700  data[cols[n]] = std::vector<T>(col_buf, col_buf+shape[0]);
701  };
702  delete[] col_buf;
703  };
704 
705  // Metadata attributes
706  std::string path; ///< path in file to the data
707  int shape [2]; ///< table shape, rows x columns.
708  std::vector<std::string> cols; ///< column names
709  /// mapping from column names to column data
710  std::map<std::string, std::vector<T> > data;
711 
712  //
713  // operator overloads
714  //
715  /// index into the table by column name (string)
716  std::vector<T> operator[] (std::string col_name)
717  {
718  return data[col_name];
719  };
720 
721  /// index into the table by row
722  std::map<std::string, T> operator[] (int m)
723  {
724  std::map<std::string, T> row = std::map<std::string, T>();
725 
726  for(int n = 0; n < shape[1]; n++)
727  row[cols[n]] = data[cols[n]][m];
728 
729  return row;
730  };
731  };
732

734  /// Create an HDF5 data type for complex 128 bit data, which happens to match the
735  /// complex data type that is used by PyTables ^_~.
736  inline hid_t _get_PYTABLES_COMPLEX128()
737  {
738  hid_t ct = H5Tcreate(H5T_COMPOUND, sizeof(xd_complex_t));
739  H5Tinsert(ct, "r", HOFFSET(xd_complex_t, re), H5T_NATIVE_DOUBLE);
740  H5Tinsert(ct, "i", HOFFSET(xd_complex_t, im), H5T_NATIVE_DOUBLE);
741  return ct;
742  };

744  /// The HDF5 id for a complex data type compatible with PyTables generated data.
745  static hid_t PYTABLES_COMPLEX128 = _get_PYTABLES_COMPLEX128();

748  /// Determines if a path exists in an hdf5 file.
749  /// \param h5file HDF5 file id for an open file.
750  /// \param path path to the data in the open file.
751  /// \return true or false
752  inline bool path_exists(hid_t h5file, std::string path)
753  {
754  bool rtn = false;
755  hid_t ds = H5Dopen2(h5file, path.c_str(), H5P_DEFAULT);
756  if (0 <= ds)
757  {
758  rtn = true;
759  H5Dclose(ds);
760  }
761  else
762  {
763  hid_t grp = H5Gopen2(h5file, path.c_str(), H5P_DEFAULT);
764  if (0 <= grp)
765  {
766  rtn = true;
767  H5Gclose(grp);
768  }
769  }
770  return rtn;
771  };

1004  /// \name isnuclide functions
1005  /// \{
1006  /// These functions test if an input \a nuc is a valid nuclide.
1007  /// \param nuc a possible nuclide
1008  /// \return a bool
1009  bool isnuclide(std::string nuc);
1010  bool isnuclide(const char * nuc);

1014  /// \name iselement functions
1015  /// \{
1016  /// These functions test if an input \a nuc is a valid element.
1017  /// \param nuc a possible element
1018  /// \return a bool
1019  bool iselement(std::string nuc);
1020  bool iselement(const char * nuc);
1021  bool iselement(int nuc);
1022 
1023  /// \}
1024  /// \name Identifier Form Functions
1025  /// \{
1026  /// The 'id' nuclide naming convention is the canonical form for representing
1027  /// nuclides in PyNE. This is termed a ZAS, or ZZZAAASSSS, representation because
1028  /// It stores 3 Z-number digits, 3 A-number digits, followed by 4 S-number digits
1029  /// which the nucleus excitation state.
1030  ///
1031  /// The id() function will always return an nuclide in id form, if successful.
1032  /// If the input nuclide is in id form already, then this is function does no
1033  /// work. For all other formats, the id() function provides a best-guess based
1034  /// on a heirarchy of other formats that is used to resolve ambiguities between
1035  /// naming conventions. For integer input the form resolution order is:
1036  /// - id
1037  /// - zz (elemental z-num only given)
1038  /// - zzaaam
1039  /// - cinder (aaazzzm)
1040  /// - mcnp
1041  /// - zzaaa
1042  /// For string (or char *) input the form resolution order is as follows:
1043  /// - ZZ-LL-AAAM
1044  /// - Integer form in a string representation, uses interger resolution
1045  /// - NIST
1046  /// - name form
1047  /// - Serpent
1048  /// - LL (element symbol)
1049  /// For well-defined situations where you know ahead of time what format the
1050  /// nuclide is in, you should use the various form_to_id() functions, rather
1051  /// than the id() function which is meant to resolve possibly ambiquous cases.
1052  /// \param nuc a nuclide
1053  /// \return nucid 32-bit integer identifier
1054  int id(int nuc);
1055  int id(const char * nuc);
1056  int id(std::string nuc);
1057  /// \}
1058 
1059  /// \name Name Form Functions
1060  /// \{
1061  /// The 'name' nuclide naming convention is the more common, human readable
1062  /// notation. The chemical symbol (one or two characters long) is first, followed
1063  /// by the nucleon number. Lastly if the nuclide is metastable, the letter M is
1064  /// concatenated to the end. For example, H-1 and Am242M are both valid.
1065  /// Note that nucname will always return name form with dashes removed, the
1066  /// chemical symbol used for letter casing (ie 'Pu'), and a trailing upercase 'M'
1067  /// for a metastable flag. The name() function first converts functions to id form
1068  /// using the id() function. Thus the form order resolution for id() also applies
1069  /// here.
1070  /// \param nuc a nuclide
1071  /// \return a string nuclide identifier.
1072  std::string name(int nuc);
1073  std::string name(const char * nuc);
1074  std::string name(std::string nuc);
1075  /// \}
1076 
1077  /// \name Z-Number Functions
1078  /// \{
1079  /// The Z-number, or charge number, represents the number of protons in a
1080  /// nuclide. This function returns that number.
1081  /// \param nuc a nuclide
1082  /// \return an integer Z-number.
1083  int znum(int nuc);
1084  int znum(const char * nuc);
1085  int znum(std::string nuc);
1086  /// \}
1087 
1088  /// \name A-Number Functions
1089  /// \{
1090  /// The A-number, or nucleon number, represents the number of protons and
1091  /// neutrons in a nuclide. This function returns that number.
1092  /// \param nuc a nuclide
1093  /// \return an integer A-number.
1094  int anum(int nuc);
1095  int anum(const char * nuc);
1096  int anum(std::string nuc);
1097  /// \}
1098 
1099  /// \name S-Number Functions
1100  /// \{
1101  /// The S-number, or excitation state number, represents the excitation
1102  /// level of a nuclide. Normally, this is zero. This function returns
1103  /// that number.
1104  /// \param nuc a nuclide
1105  /// \return an integer A-number.
1106  int snum(int nuc);
1107  int snum(const char * nuc);
1108  int snum(std::string nuc);
1109  /// \}
1110 
1111  /// \name ZZAAAM Form Functions
1112  /// \{
1113  /// The ZZAAAM nuclide naming convention is the former canonical form for
1114  /// nuclides in PyNE. This places the charge of the nucleus out front, then has
1115  /// three digits for the atomic mass number, and ends with a metastable flag
1116  /// (0 = ground, 1 = first excited state, 2 = second excited state, etc).
1117  /// Uranium-235 here would be expressed as 922350.
1118  /// \param nuc a nuclide
1119  /// \return an integer nuclide identifier.
1120  int zzaaam(int nuc);
1121  int zzaaam(const char * nuc);
1122  int zzaaam(std::string nuc);
1123  /// \}
1124

1271  std::string nist(std::string nuc);
1272  /// \}

1275  /// \{
1276  /// This converts from the NIST nuclide naming convention
1277  /// to the id canonical form for nuclides in PyNE.
1278  /// \param nuc a nuclide in NIST form.
1279  /// \return an integer id nuclide identifier.
1280  //int serpent_to_id(int nuc); NON-EXISTANT
1281  int nist_to_id(const char * nuc);
1282  int nist_to_id(std::string nuc);
1283  /// \}
1284 
1285  /// \name CINDER Form Functions
1286  /// \{
1287  /// This is the naming convention used by the CINDER burnup library.
1288  /// The CINDER format is similar to zzaaam form except that the placement of the
1289  /// Z- and A-numbers are swapped. Therefore, this format is effectively aaazzzm.
1290  /// For example, 2420951 is the valid cinder notation for AM242M.
1291  /// \param nuc a nuclide
1292  /// \return a string nuclide identifier.
1293  int cinder(int nuc);
1294  int cinder(const char * nuc);
1295  int cinder(std::string nuc);
1296  /// \}

1299  /// \{
1300  /// This converts from the Cinder nuclide naming convention
1301  /// to the id canonical form for nuclides in PyNE.
1302  /// \param nuc a nuclide in Cinder form.
1303  /// \return an integer id nuclide identifier.
1304  int cinder_to_id(int nuc);
1305  int cinder_to_id(const char * nuc);
1306  int cinder_to_id(std::string nuc);
1307  /// \}
1308 
1309  /// \name ALARA Form Functions
1310  /// \{
1311  /// This is the format used in the ALARA activation code elements library.
1312  /// For elements, the form is "ll" where ll is the atomic symbol. For isotopes
1313  /// the form is "ll:AAA". No metastable isotope flag is used.
1314  /// \param nuc a nuclide
1315  /// \return a string nuclide identifier.
1316  std::string alara(int nuc);
1317  std::string alara(const char * nuc);
1318  std::string alara(std::string nuc);
1319  /// \}
1320

1322  /// \{
1323  /// This converts from the ALARA nuclide naming convention
1324  /// to the id canonical form for nuclides in PyNE.

1326  /// \return an integer id nuclide identifier.
1327  //int alara_to_id(int nuc); NOT POSSIBLE
1328  int alara_to_id(const char * nuc);
1329  int alara_to_id(std::string nuc);
1330  /// \}
1331 
1332  /// \name SZA Form Functions
1333  /// \{
1334  /// This is the new format for ACE data tables in the form SSSZZZAAA.
1335  /// The first three digits represent the excited state (000 = ground,
1336  /// 001 = first excited state, 002 = second excited state, etc).
1337  /// The second three digits are the atomic number and the last three
1338  /// digits are the atomic mass. Prepending zeros can be omitted, making
1339  /// the SZA form equal to the MCNP form for non-excited nuclides.
1340  /// \param nuc a nuclide
1341  /// \return a string nuclide identifier.
1342  int sza(int nuc);
1343  int sza(const char * nuc);
1344  int sza(std::string nuc);
1345  /// \}
1346

1348  /// \{
1349  /// This converts from the SZA nuclide naming convention
1350  /// to the id canonical form for nuclides in PyNE.
1351  /// \param nuc a nuclide in SZA form.
1352  /// \return an integer id nuclide identifier.
1353  int sza_to_id(int nuc);
1354  int sza_to_id(const char * nuc);
1355  int sza_to_id(std::string nuc);
1356  /// \}
1357 
1358  /// \name Ground State Form Functions
1359  /// \{
1360  /// This form stores the nuclide in id form, but removes
1361  /// the state information about the nuclide. I is in the same
1362  /// form as ID, but the four last digits are all zeros.
1363  /// \param nuc a nuclide
1364  /// \return a integer groundstate id
1365  inline int groundstate(int nuc) {return (id(nuc) / 10000 ) * 10000;};
1366  inline int groundstate(std::string nuc) {return groundstate(id(nuc));};
1367  inline int groundstate(const char * nuc) {return groundstate(std::string(nuc));};
1368  /// \}
1369 
1370  /// \name State Map functions
1371  /// \{
1372  /// These convert from/to decay state ids (used in decay data)
1373  /// to metastable ids (the PyNE default)
1374  void _load_state_map();
1375  int state_id_to_id(int state);
1376  int id_to_state_id(int nuc_id);
1377  extern std::map<int, int> state_id_map;
1378  /// \}
1379 
1380  /// \name ENSDF Form Functions
1381  /// \{
1382  /// This converts id's stored using standard ensdf syntax to nuc_id's
1383  /// \param ensdf nuc string
1384  /// \return PyNE nuc_id
1385  int ensdf_to_id(const char * nuc);
1386  int ensdf_to_id(std::string nuc);
1387  /// \}
1388 
1389 };

3160  /** \brief Represents a <a HREF="http://www.json.org">JSON</a> value.
3161  *
3162  * This class is a discriminated union wrapper that can represents a:
3163  * - signed integer [range: Value::minInt - Value::maxInt]
3164  * - unsigned integer (range: 0 - Value::maxUInt)
3165  * - double
3166  * - UTF-8 string
3167  * - boolean
3168  * - 'null'
3169  * - an ordered list of Value
3170  * - collection of name/value pairs (javascript object)
3171  *
3172  * The type of the held value is represented by a #ValueType and
3173  * can be obtained using type().
3174  *
3175  * values of an #objectValue or #arrayValue can be accessed using operator[]() methods.
3176  * Non const methods will automatically create the a #nullValue element
3177  * if it does not exist.
3178  * The sequence of an #arrayValue will be automatically resize and initialized
3179  * with #nullValue. resize() can be used to enlarge or truncate an #arrayValue.
3180  *
3181  * The get() methods can be used to obtanis default value in the case the required element
3182  * does not exist.
3183  *
3184  * It is possible to iterate over the list of a #objectValue values using
3185  * the getMemberNames() method.
3186  */

3721  /** \brief A linked page based hash-table implementation used internally by Value.
3722  * \internal ValueInternalMap is a tradional bucket based hash-table, with a linked
3723  * list in each bucket to handle collision. There is an addional twist in that
3724  * each node of the collision linked list is a page containing a fixed amount of
3725  * value. This provides a better compromise between memory usage and speed.
3726  *
3727  * Each bucket is made up of a chained list of ValueInternalLink. The last
3728  * link of a given bucket can be found in the 'previous_' field of the following bucket.
3729  * The last link of the last bucket is stored in tailLink_ as it has no following bucket.
3730  * Only the last link of a bucket may contains 'available' item. The last link always
3731  * contains at least one element unless is it the bucket one very first link.

3820  /** \brief A simplified deque implementation used internally by Value.
3821  * \internal
3822  * It is based on a list of fixed "page", each page contains a fixed number of items.
3823  * Instead of using a linked-list, a array of pointer is used for fast item look-up.
3824  * Look-up for an element is as follow:
3825  * - compute page index: pageIndex = itemIndex / itemsPerPage
3826  * - look-up item in page: pages_[pageIndex][itemIndex % itemsPerPage]
3827  *
3828  * Insertion is amortized constant time (only the array containing the index of pointers
3829  * need to be reallocated when items are appended).
3830  */
